column168: DOT 5800 Form Template – NAR in Yard with contractor response   On 07/01/2019 at around 1400 hours EST CSXT FRA Inspector reported that the vapor line plug was not installed and the vapor line was in the open position on GATX7376, a residue tank car of Sulfuric Acid located at MP OA 641.70 in Brusnwick, GA. The car was isolated and the shipper, Trammo, was notified. Hepaco, a CSXT response contractor, responded and the vapor line in the open position and the vapor line plug not installed. The issue identified and corrective actions were communicated to the shipper, Trammo (Andy Martin 813-940-7737).  Hepaco secured the vapor line and secured the vapor line plug.  The car was released.    NAR Cause Code: 328 – Vapor line closure cap less than tool tight  5(4+5+0) x (2+0) = 90 NARRI   Brunswick, GA 07/01/19 – GATX7376 Sulfuric Acid

column168: During the loading of an outbound 53' 10 Day van, the material handler attempted to place the 5 gallon drum containing the hydrochloric acid into a space between two adjacent pallets containing 55 gallon drums. When he placed the drum from an approximate height of one foot, the bottom of the drum contacted the corner of the wood pallet below causing a small crack in the drum. The drum was immediately retrieved and placed upside down on the floor so that the material inside the drum could not come in contact with the small crack. All warehouse personnel were notified of the small spill and proceeded to place absorbent pads and vermiculite on the van floor absorbing the minimal amount of material. Approximately 500 ml of material seeped through the floor cracked and dripped on to the asphalt parking lot beneath the van. This was removed using absorbent pads(photo attached).
column169: Procedures for loading vans were reviewed with warehouse personnel.

On July 2, 2019, at 1055 ET, ERTS was contacted by XPO Logistics Terminal UDV regarding a cargo release.  It was reported that due to defective packaging, (1) 5-gallon poly pail of Heavy Duty Brown Degreaser (Corrosive liquid, n.o.s., UN1760) released approximately 2 gallons of product on to the trailer floor.  Terminal personnel cleaned up the release with absorbents and the proper PPE.  The damaged container, spent absorbents, and all other debris were containerized in (1) 55-gallon poly drum.  The waste drum was then staged onsite at OS&D for terminal personnel to manage.

PER SCREENING AGENT'S REPORT IT: REGARDING AWB 2560 9721, ON 07/01/19 AT 1845, WHILE SCREENING SHIPMENT TENDERED AS AUTO PARTS VIA X-RAY, IMAGE REVEALED WHAT APPEARED TO BE FOUR (4) SMALL CONTAINERS OF ADHESIVE.  OPENED SHIPMENT AND CONFIRMED FOUR CONTAINERS OF PERMATEX THREAD SEALANT, UN1133 ADHESIVE LIMITED QUANTITY, CLASS 3, PG III.

At 2053 EST, ERTS received a call from XPO regarding a hazardous cargo release of UN3265, 8, PG II, Mergal K12N. Reported that due to improper loading from the previous terminal (XSL), one 55-gallon plastic drums was punctured while unloading due to a forklift accident, causing  30-gallons to release at the nose of the trailer #311929 floor and on the concrete. The spill was mitigated by laying the drum on its side. There were no drains, soils, or waterways impacted by this incident.   Contractors onsite confirm 30 gals of product impacted a 25 ft x 10 ft area of concrete parking lot under the trailer and a 5 ft x 5 ft area of trailer floor. Absorbents were used and containerized into a 55 gallon poly drum, the damaged drum was overpacked with a 95 gallon poly overpack. All waste was left on sight for terminal personnel to manage.

column168: Passenger checked baggage which consisted of a utility mop/bucket on 07/08/2019 for HA654 HNL-LNY (AC Tail Number N806HC). Passenger did not disclose that he checked a bottle of DCT Oven Cleaner (UN1814 Hazard Class: Class 8 Corrosive UN 1814 Quantity Size: 1 liter). Passenger was questioned by customer service agent prior to checking his baggage whether hazardous materials were present and he stated he did not have any hazardous material.  Upon arrival in LNY and during the off-loading of baggage from the aircraft, LNY Ramp agent Kekai Biho, informed his supervisor that while unloading checked luggage from the cargo area he observed a box to be wet and smelled a strong unknown chemical odor from the area.  When he lifted the box, a bottle fell from the box which he determined to be oven cleaner and notified the flight crew.  The entire 1 liter bottle of oven cleaner leaked throughout the cargo hold of the aircraft. LNY AARF was called to the scene to assist in cleanup and ARFF was unable to provide cleanup assistance and the aircraft is currently down due to corrosive spill of undeclared hazmat in a passenger checked bag Aircraft is awaiting MX inspection/cleanup. Aircraft was out of service for 4 hours. The following files have been included as attachments to the report: Passenger ID SDS for Oven Cleaner Dangerous Goods Report for 49CFR175.13  When delivering the checked box to baggage claim, the customer was asked what contents were in the bottle.  His response was "Simple Green" cleaning solution.
column169: Root Cause of the incident was that the passenger knowingly checked a hazardous material that is prohibited to be carried on the aircraft in passenger checked baggage. HA customer service agents properly questioned passenger on whether prohibited items were contained in checked baggage and passenger acknowledge that no prohibited items were in the checked baggage.

During approach to CAE MTN7500, an ATR-42 N915FX, a strong odor of acetone was observed by both crew members. Upon landing and after arriving at the gate, the ground crew unloading the aircraft was informed that there may be a box of undeclared DG that had spilled. They were also informed to advise the crew if any box was found with the odor/Ieaking. Upon reaching zone 4 in the aircraft, the box was located and found to be Ieaking. The box was removed by the DG specialist for examination, and the zone was cleaned by the DG specialist. Photographs are attached of the floorboard of the aircraft and of the package. The contents of the package were determined to be PVC/CPVC Primer. There was no indication on the box of what was in it and the box was not listed on the DG manifest provided by FedEx.

column168: On 7/2/19 received notification from Hub personnel that unit JBHU 291069 was reported to be leaking a syrup type substance from the bottom of the container floor, spilling approximately 1 pint of product on the ground. WB listed this shipment containing multiple types of hazardous commodities, customer dispatched Patriot Environmental Services to assess and to remediate the reported leaking shipment.  Interior inspection performed by Patriot Environmental Services revealed mixed palletized freight varying in sizes and weights, cargo was stowed two rows wide with and stacked with a partial second layer. The load was secured with an improperly applied strip of ty   guard at the rear of the load, as a form of doorway securement. A pallet of (5) gallon pails containing "Mudslide" (cleaning concentrate\ hazardous corrosive UN3265) was found collapsed damaging (5) pails that resulted in (25) gallons of product loss that spilled inside the container. Responder was able to clean up the spilling product and remediated contaminated areas.

While offloading a trailer at the Veolia, West Carrollton, OH facility, an employee noticed that several  containers had shifted while in transit.  After investigating the pallet in question, the employee noticed the shrink wrapping had come loose during transportation allowing the containers to fall over.  While  several containers were found laying on their side only one container was leaking.  Liquid had begun to slowly drip from around the lid and a small pool (less than one gallon) was forming under the  container.  The Veolia employee set the containers upright and remediated the spill.  The lid was  secured back on the container and all were safely moved into the facility for processing.  The  employee's quick response prevented any further spill or collection of hazardous material inside the  trailer.  The material never left the trailer or spilled outside of containment.
column169: Veolia West Carrollton management shared this incident (photos, report and response) with members of the team from the initial loading facility.  The loading facility should provide retraining on load  securement with the employees assigned to loading their trailers.

column168: On July 14, 2019, at 04:13 hours personnel in the CSXT Russell, KY yard reported product leaking from the top of tank car SHPX 215067, a load of Glacial Acetic Acid.  The car was isolated and the shipper, Eastman Chemical, was notified via CHEMTREC Report #2019-0714-00004.  Quick Response, a CSXT response contractor, was dispatched and found the source of the release was due to an improperly secure manway cover.  The manway cover was not properly aligned with the manway nozzle.  Quick Response personnel were able to tighten three of the manway cover bolts which caused the cover to properly align and secure the release.  The issue’s identified and corrective actions were communicated to shipper’s representative: Ms. Melissa McCaslin.  The car was released for transportation.

At approximately 2000 hours, a Clean Harbors Environmental Services Inc. driver was pulled over by a Texas Department of Public Services State Trooper for a Roadside Inspection of the commercial motor vehicle he was operating. During the inspection, the officer discovered that 5-gallon drum of palatalized material had become unsecured, fallen over, leaked approximately 1 gallon of its material contained inside. Absorbent material was immediately put down around the pallet to stop any further spillage. At the officer’s discretion, the driver was allowed to don the appropriate PPE, and cleaned up the spill. The Spilled material and absorbent materials used to remediate the spill were properly packaged, marked, and labeled and sent for disposal. TXDPS Citation number: TX5HXK0VEHUI.
column169: An investigation into the spill incident revealed that the spillage occurred due to improper preparation for transportation and improper load securement. The driver and dock personnel at the point of origin were retrained in proper preparation, container closure and inspection procedures, and load securement and blocking and bracing techniques.

At approximately 1530 hours Central Standard Time, a Clean Harbors Environmental Services, Inc. dock employee working at a Clean Harbors Environmental Services, Inc. facility located at 500 Independence Parkway, La Porte, Texas, 77571, noticed a spill on the inside floor of the trailer during the unloading process. Absorbent material was immediately put down and the spent product was contained. An in-house response crew responded to the spill, donned the appropriated PPE, and cleaned up the spill. Spilled material and absorbent materials used to remediate the spill were properly packaged, marked, and labeled and sent for disposal.
column169: An investigation into the spill incident revealed that the spill was due to the commodity’s polymerization while in-transit. The generator was contacted to discuss any changes to their loading process which could have caused cross contamination of chemicals leading up to the incident. It was discovered that customer’s process of loading drums included the use of a 5 gallon pail which was marked and labeled to be used for the appropriate materials, was possibly used for the wrong material by an inattentive employee. Clean Harbors’ management team offered the customer recommendations to amend the drum loading process which includes instituting the use of a smaller 1 gallon pail to be filled with materials and monitor for any possible reactions before placing materials into 55-gallon drums.

column62: Conveyer or Material Handling Equipment Mishap
column168: Warehouse personnel were offloading a van trailer with a forklift and using drum picker attachment.   The warehouse employee picked up the drum and the snap ring peeled off the drum causing 6 ounces  of material to spill onto the floor of the trailer.  The employee quickly set the drum down and turned  off the forklift in order to reseal the damaged drum. A response crew was summoned, donned the appropriate personal protective equipment and  resealed the drum and cleaned  up the trailer floor.  The shipment was then loaded without further  incident.
column169: The forklift operator was advised to use better care and caution when loading and unloading drums.   Forklift operator was pulled from the forklift and not permitted to operate the forklift until training is  completed.  Additionally all drivers and warehouse personnel have been retrained to no longer use  the drum picker attachment to pick up snap ring style covers.

On July 4, 2019, at 2035 hours, a Transportation Manager at the Conrail Pavonia Yard, Camden, New  Jersey reported that UTLX 205342, a loaded tank car of UN1090, Acetone was leaking from the top of  the tank car and had exposed a conductor while switching the tank car. The tank car was isolated and  the shipper Advansix,  were notified directly   The conductor was taken to Cooper Hospital and given  prescription cough medicine to address any chemical cough. Conrail spoke directly with Dan Sekel,  Advansix Rail Coordinator (215) 807-8445 and decided to do a joint inspection the following morning.  The leak was only active during movement.  Hepaco, a Conrail response contractor,  Advansix representative David Watrous, and Conrail met  onsite at 08:00 on July 5, 2019 to perform a complete inspection of tank car UTLX 205342.  Upon  inspection it was found that all six of six manway securement bolts were in the down position with  the intended seal and paperwork still located atop the manway cover. It was agreed that the tank  car was inadequately prepared for transportation prior to offering it to Conrail for movement.  NARRI: 5x(5+3+0)x(3+5) = 320 Cause code:200

column168: On July 24, 2019, at 0006 EST, XPO Logistics Terminal LSX notified ERTS of a release of UN1760 "GC Concentrate Plus Tortilla Preservative System" from a 330 gallon poly tote. ERTS dispatched contractors to conduct all on site cleanup and over packing operations. At 0210 EST, contractors arrived on site and confirmed the product impacted a slab of wood placed under the tote and did not migrate. A small pinhole puncture was found at the bottom of the tote with the cause of the puncture being unknown. At 0235 EST, contractors completed conducting the tote transfer and salvaged 270 gallons of product. At 0311 EST, the original labeling was placed onto the new tote and the damaged tote was cut up, along with the impacted wood slab. All waste was containerized into a 55-gallon poly drum which was staged on site for terminal personnel to manage. Contractors departed site at 0315 EST.

column62: Impact with Sharp or Protruding Object (e.g., nails)
column168: On July 27, 2019, at 0120 EST, XPO Logistics Terminal XCW notified ERTS of an approximate 0.5 gallon release of UN3145 "MasterSeal 350 PART B" from a 5 gallon poly bucket to the trailer floor due to a nail puncture. ERTS determined terminal personnel could clean the release with the appropriate provided PPE. Terminal personnel containerized the waste into a 55 gallon poly drum which was staged on site for XPO to manage.

column62: Impact with Sharp or Protruding Object (e.g., nails)
column168: While transferring hazardous waste drums from one trailer to another trailer, a 55 gallon poly drum was pierced with the drum dolly.  The drum was rolled onto its side with the hole facing up and was  subsequently overpacked.  An estimated 1 gallon of sodium hydroxide was released from the drum.

column168: On July 19, 2019, at approximately 11:00 hours, while conducting a routine compliance inspection at the Radnor Yard in Nashville, TN, CSX Hazardous Materials Team members discovered UTLX 203249, a loaded tank car of Methyl Methacrylate was leaking vapors from the top of the car.  The release was due to a faulty vacuum relief valve.  The car was isolated and the shipper, Evonik Cyro, was notified via CHEMTREC report 2019-0719-00294.  Marion Environmental, Inc. (MEI), a CSX emergency response contractor, was dispatched to assist with the release.  Response personnel from MEI and CSX removed the faulty component and blinded the opening to the car’s pressure plate by installing a two and a half inch threaded pipe plug. These corrective measures were communicated to Mr. Van Evra, with Evonik Cyro.  Evonik.  The car was subsequently released for transportation on an OTMA-3.

The AST did not have a berm to contain the spill. US Ecology arrived promptly and began remediation.
column169: Smith system GOAL method of Get Out And Look, as well as additional training will help prevent recurrence. Cusco Vac truck, #4086, was parked at the Bristol CT waste water treatment facility. Due to a lab error, the truck could not be off loaded until the sample was corrected. During that time the truck was moved from the containment pad to the general parking area so another tanker could be off loaded. The valves on truck #4086 were held slightly open by debris in the dip tank that was being cleaned. The employees used an aluminum reducer and cap instead of stainless steel, and when the acid mixture leaked past the valves, it corroded the reducer, and allowed acid to leak on to the ground. An employee of the treatment plant discovered the leak, and notified the plant manager. The spill response team was dispatched to the facility. The team, using proper PPE, contained the spill. They removed the reducer, and capped of the valve with a cap made of the proper material. The area was then cleaned, with the affected gravel being removed. All of the contaminated material was placed in proper containers and disposed of.
column169: All of the vac trucks from this branch are being inventoried to ensure the caps. plugs, and reducers are made of the compatible material for the waste that is being picked up. All employees are being re-trained in the use of reducers, and which material is compatible for the waste being picked up. All employees are being retrained in the proper shut down procedures for a vac truck to ensure the valves are free of debris, and will not be held open.  Vac truck #4086 had the valves inspected for damage.

column168: On July 5, 2019 at 2030 EST, United Vision Logistics experienced a 10-gallon release of UN3286, Flammable liquid, toxic, corrosive, n.o.s., 3, PGII released from (1) 550-gallon metal tote due to a bad fitting on the tote, causing it to leak from the threads. ERTS dispatched OMI - Oil Mop for emergency response and cleanup activities. At 2255 EST, OMI arrived on site and confirmed that approximately 10-gallons of product had released to a 3' x 10' area of the trailer and asphalt below. The contractor wiped the impacted areas with absorbent pads then applied granular absorbents. The spent absorbents were placed inside (2) 55-gallon poly waste drums. The contractor transferred the remaining product in the leaking tote into (2) new poly totes with a 1" diaphragm pump. The contractor reported that the fire department rinsed down the parking lot. The contractor finished the cleanup and tote transfer at 0435 EST and departed the site with the waste.

column168: SUPERVISOR INFORMED RESPONDER OF ACTIVE HAZMAT LEAKER ON THE UNDER SLIDE OF BOX LINE 3. UPON APPROACH THE RESPONDER COULD SMELL THE CONTENTS AND FOUND THE PACKAGE AT THE BASE OF THE STEPS VISIBLY LEAKING AND HAD LEAKED A CONSIDERABLE AMOUNT THAT HAD SPREAD ACROSS THE FLOOR. RESPONDER PROMPTLY PUT PACKAGE INTO SPILL TUB TO CONTAIN THE LEAKING. THE SUPERVISOR WAS ASKED HOW THE PACKAGE ENDED UP ON THE FLOOR FROM THE UNDER SLIDE AND WAS TOLD THE TOP SLIDER SAID IT WAS A HAZMAT THAT NEEDED TO BE REPACKAGED. TOP SLIDER THEN SENT THE PACKAGE TO THE UNDER SLIDE UNAWARE ANY DAMAGE HAD OCCURRED. ANOTHER TOP SLIDER HAD INFORMED THE SUPERVISOR THAT THE UNDER SLID PACKAGE WAS NOW LEAKING. THE CALL WAS MADE AT THAT TIME AND PRESUMABLY MOVED TO THE FLOOR TO KEEP IT FROM OTHER PACKAGES. RESPONDER ADVISED SUPERVISOR AND TOP SLIDERS TO REMAIN CLEAR OF THE AREA. CONTENTS WERE PH TESTED AND FOUND TO BE STRONGLY ALKALINE. SODIUM BICARBONATE WAS USED TO NEUTRALIZE IT AND UNIVERSAL CLAY ABSORBENT WAS USED TO SOLIDIFY THE SPILL.
CALLED TO UNLOAD FOR LEAKING HAZ MAT. CONSULTED DECISION TREE  RESPONSE SHEETS, DONNED PROPER PPE. PKG NOT LEAKING ON SURROUNDINGS. TRANSPORTED BACK TO DMP AREA FOR FURTHER PROCESSING.

column168: At 1506 Kyle Goodwin with Dupre notified ERTS the landing gear on unit 811226 caused the tanker to split open and release 100 gallons of gasoline to the underlying concrete pad. FD responded and placed absorbents onto impacted area.  ERTS sent  Lone Star Hazmat Response LLC  arrival of 16:30 for remediation. Contractor confirmed the 100 gallons of spillage impacted the concrete pad and soil. He also inspected the property for any drains or utilities the fuel could have migrated to and the closest drain is 500' + feet from the site, which areas were not affected. Contractor used 1- 55 gallon drum Poly drum for removal of the spill.  In addition absorbents and PPE were used as remediation. Contractor place micro blaze to affected area the next day 7/17 0902 as a preventive measure to the concrete pad.

column17: JR SIMPLOT COMPANY; D.B.A. - SIMPLOT GROWER SOLUTIONSJ R SIMPLOT COMPANY
column25: JR SIMPLOT COMPANY; D.B.A - SIMPLOT GROWER SOLUTIONS
column168: A JR SIMPLOT EMPLOYEE FROM OUR SGS CHEYENNE WELLS LOCATION WAS IN THE PROCESS OF TRANSPORTATION ANHYDROUS AMMONIA USING (2) 1,000 GALLON NURSE TRAILERS TO J AND A FARMS LLC AT 435 JACKRABBIT RD IN WESKAN, KS. WHILE HEADING EAST ON HIGHWAY 40 ABOUT 2.5 MILES FROM CHEYENNE WELLS OUR DRIVER HIT A GUARDRAIL WITH THE REAR NURSE TRAILER. THE DRIVER STATED THAT HE WAS DRIVING ALONG WHEN HE NOTICED SOMETHING WRONG WITH HIS REAR NURSE TRAILER. BY THE TIME HE COULD REACT, THE REAR TRAILER HIT THE GUARDRAIL AND OVERTURNED. ONCE THE DRIVER STOPPED, HE STARTED MAKING EMERGENCY NOTIFICATIONS AT 8:48AM. OUR DRIVER STATED THAT A BROKEN SPINDLE OR FAULTY BEARING WAS THE LIKELY CAUSE FOR HIM TO LOSE CONTROL OF THE REAR TRAILER. THE STATE OF COLORADO TRAFFIC ACCIDENT REPORT STATES THAT THE MOST LIKELY CAUSE WAS THE DRIVER WAS DISTRACTED AND DRIFTED OVER TO THE SHOULDER STRIKING THE GUARD RAIL.  FIRST RESPONDERS FROM THE CHEYENNE WELLS FIRE DEPARTMENT AND COLORADO STATE PATROL WERE ON SCENE SHORTLY. THE STATE PATROL SHUTDOWN HIGHWAY 40 AND THE FIRE DEPARTMENT STARTED SPRAYING WATER ON THE TANK TO CONTROL THE VENTING VAPORS FROM THE NURSE TANK.  THE FIRE DEPARTMENT REPORTED TO US THAT THE TANKS VALVES HAD BEEN TORN OFF IN THE ACCIDENT. THE TRAILER HIT THE GUARDRAIL AND OVERTURNED ON TOP OF THE GUARDRAIL. IN DOING SO, THE ROLL CAGE AND TOP OF THE TANK, INCLUDING THE VALVES WERE BROKEN OFF.  APPROXIMATELY 850 GALLONS OF PRODUCT WAS LOST DURING THE INCIDENT. NO INJURIES REPORTED. NO EVACUATION REPORTED. HIGHWAY 40 REOPENED BY NOON.
column169: DUE TO THIS INCIDENT WE WILL REVIEW INSPECTION/MAINTENANCE RECORDS FOR NURSE TANKS. BEARINGS ON THIS TRAILER WERE REPACKED LESS THAN A YEAR AGO AND NO NOTES WERE MADE ON THE SPINDLE FOR UNUSUAL WEAR OR DAMAGE. OUR INSPECTION AND MAINTENANCE FORMS WILL BE UPDATED TO INCLUDE SPECIFIC INSPECTION OF THE UNDERCARRIAGE INTEGRITY, INCLUDING WELDS AND FRAME CONDITION.  DRIVERS THAT TRANSPORT NURSE TRAILERS ARE BEING INFORMED OF THE INCIDENT. THEY ARE REVIEWING WHAT WE DID IN THIS INCIDENT AND HOW WE CAN IMPROVE OUR NOTIFICATION PROCESS. THEY ARE ALSO BEING PROVIDED ADDITIONAL TRAINING IN DRIVER AWARENESS AND DISTRACTED DRIVING, PRE AND POST VEHICLE INSPECTIONS, AND EMERGENCY RESPONSE PLANS.  SHOULD YOU HAVE ANY QUESTIONS OR NEED ADDITIONAL INFORMATION, PLEASE DO NOT HESITATE TO CONTACT ME BY PHONE AT 208-780-7523 OR EMAIL AT DUSTIN.ELDREDGE@SIMPLOT.COM

column42: BATTERIES, WET, FILLED WITH ACID, ELECTRIC STORAGE
column168: THE INCIDENT OCCURRED, JULY 1, 2019, AT THE INTERSECTION OF GOVERNOR STOCKLEY RD. (CR432) AND ROUTE 113 (DUPONT BLVD). ROUTE 113 IS TWO LANES NORTHBOUND AND TWO LANES SOUTHBOUND, DIVIDED BY A GRASS MEDIAN STRIP. ROUTE 113 IN THE AREA OF THE CRASH IS POSTED AT 55 MPH. IN THE AREA OF THE CRASH THERE ARE NO TRAFFIC LIGHTS OR SIGNALS. GOVERNOR STOCKLEY RD. IS CONTROLLED BY STOP SIGNS. ROUTE 113 HAS THE RIGHT OF WAY.  OUR DRIVER HAD JUST MADE A DELIVERY AT AUTO PLUS IN MILLSBORO, DE. HE WAS HEADING NORTHBOUND ON ROUTE 113 AND 13 MILES NORTH OF MILLSBORO, DE, GOING APPROXIMATELY 55 MPH. AT THE INTERSECTION, A VEHICLE CAME FROM OUR DRIVERS LEFT SIDE, TRAVELING EAST ON GOVERNOR STOCKLEY RD. THIS VEHICLE DID NOT STOP OR YIELD RIGHT OF WAY AND PROCEEDED INTO THE PATH OF OUR DRIVER, HEADING ACROSS ROUTE 113. OUR DRIVER DID NOT HAVE TIME TO PERFORM BRAKE OR PERFORM ANY TYPOE OF EVASIVE MANEUVER. IMPACT WAS MADE IN THE NORTHBOUND LANE OF ROUTE 113. THE FRONT OF OUR TRUCK IMPACTED THE PASSENGER SIDE OF THE OTHER VEHICLE. BOTH UNITS WERE PUSHED INTO THE NORTH EAST CORNER OF THE INTERSECTION, INTO A UTILITY POLE. WHILE ON THIS PATH OUR TRUCK ROLLED ONTO ITS SIDE AND THE TOP OF THE REAR BOX TORE OPEN, SPILLING OUR LOAD (LEAD ACID BATTERIES) ONTO THE HIGHWAY AND ROAD SIDE ALONG WITH DIESEL FUEL AND MOTOR OIL. NO STORM DRAINS OR WATERWAYS WERE IMPACTED BY THE RELEASE.  LOCAL FIRE AND RESCUE PERSONNEL ARRIVED AT THE INCIDENT LOCATION AND ASSESSED THE RELEASE. A REPRESENTATIVE FROM DNREC WAS ON-SITE AND INDICATED THAT ONLY A SMALL AREA OF IMPACTED SOIL NEEDED TO BE REMEDIATED. FIRST CALL ENVIRONMENTAL (FCE) CONFIRMED THAT AN AREA MEASURING APPROXIMATELY 8 FEET X 10 FOOT OF GRASS-SOIL WAS IMPACTED, AND COULD BE HAND EXCAVATED. FCE HAND EXCAVATED THE IMPACTED SHALLOW SOILS BETWEEN 1-2 INCHES IN DEPTH AND CONTAINERIZED INTO ONE, 55 GALLON STEEL DRUM FOR DISPOSAL. WASTE DISPOSAL FOR THIS DRUM IS STILL PENDING WAITING FOR DISPOSAL DOCUMENTATION.  THE ROAD WAS CLOSED FOR APPROXIMATELY 3 HOURS. BOTH DRIVERS WERE TAKEN TO THE HOSPITAL FOR EXAMINATION. OUR DRIVER WAS RELEASED AFTER HIS EXAMINATION. THE OTHER DRIVER NEEDED TO BE CUT OUT OF HIS VEHICLE AND WAS IN SERIOUS CONDITION. THE UTILITY POLE THAT WAS HIT NEEDED TO BE REPLACED. OUR TRUCK AND OUR LOAD OF LEAD ACID BATTERIES WERE PICKED UP AND TAKEN TO THE TOWING FACILITY. OUR TRUCK WAS DEEMED TOTALED BY OUR INSURANCE COMPANY. EAST PENN PICKED UP THE JUNK BATTERIES (142 BROKEN BATTERIES) FROM THE TOWING FACILITY TO DELIVER TO EAST PENN MANUFACTURING CO.'S SECONDARY LEAD SMELTER IN LYON STATION, PA FOR PROPER DISPOSAL AND RECYCLING.
column169: NO CHANGES OR RECOMMENDATIONS. DRIVE WAS WITHIN SCOPE/SAFETY OF COMPANY GUIDANCE. LOAD WAS SECURED PROPERLY PER REGULATIONS.

column168: At approximately 1515 hrs., Clean Harbors Environmental Services, Inc. received a phone call at a company facility located at 1722 Cooper Creek Road Building # 10, Denton, Texas, 76208 from a motorist reporting a minor leak of material from a tank vehicle under tow by a Clean Harbors Environmental Services, Inc. power unit. After receiving the call, the local management team notified the driver to pull over immediately and inspect his load. After pulling over to a safe and secure location, the driver found wet residue on the body on the tank vehicle leading from the roof of the tank vehicle near the man-way. Further investigation by the driver uncovered that the washout cap on the roof of the trailer had not been properly secured and was in the fully open position. Absorbent material was immediately put down to contain the spent product. An in-house response crew responded to the spill, donned the appropriated PPE, and cleaned up the spill. Spilled material and absorbent materials used to remediate the spill were properly packaged, marked, and labeled and sent for disposal.
column169: An internal investigation into the spill incident revealed that the washout cap had not been properly secured by the shipper’s loading team. Due to the shipper’s facility rules, 3rd party drivers are not allowed to access the roofs of tank vehicles without 3 points of contact and a fall prevention system. After the spill, Clean Harbors Environmental Services, Inc. project management and the management team of the shipper consulted. Clean Harbors Environmental Services, Inc. management determined that no loads will be taken into transport by Clean Harbors Environmental Services, Inc. drivers until the load is inspected by the shipper’s loading crew at the point of receipt, and all closures have been verified to be closed before transport.

column168: ON THE MORNING OF 07/17/2019 WE WERE NOTIFIED BY AN RTS DRIVER THAT THERE WAS A RED LIQUID DRIPPING FROM VAN #T-9019 ONTO THE PAVEMENT BELOW THE TRAILER. THE VAN WAS PARKED AT AN OFFSITE TRANSFER LINE, WAITING TO BE TRANSPORTED TO RIS FOR RECIEPT. THE MATERIAL IN THIS VANS WAS LOADED AND PICKED UP AT PETROLEUM 07/10/2019 ON MANIFEST #013080212FLE (SHIPPER 357528).  BASED ON THE SITUATION WE CONTACTED A THIRD-PARTY VENDOR TO PROVIDE ADDITIONAL RESOURCES TO ASSIST WITH THE RESPONSE. THE ER TEAM MOBILIZED TO THE SITE WITH A ROSS PROJECT MANAGER, CREW, SERVICE VEHICLES, SPILL TRAILER, TOW MOTOR WITH TRAILER, PPE AND SUPPLIES. THEY ARRIVED AT THE SITE, SETUP A CONTAINMENT AREA TO PLACE THE CONTAINERS ON AND THEN PROCEEDED TO OPEN THE VAN DOORS AND REMOVE AND INSPECT EACH CONTAINER FROM THE VAN. ABOUT TWO ROWS BACK IN THE VAN THEY CAME ACROSS A GAYLORD BOX THAT WAS LEAKING. THEY PROCEEDED TO UNLOAD ABOUT HALF THE VAN TO VERIFY IF ANY OTHER CONTAINERS WERE LEAKING. FIVE CONTAINERS IN ALL WERE FOUND TO BE LEAKING. THE BOTTOM OF ALL THE GAYLORDS WERE WET FROM THE LEAKS AND WERE NOT IN DOT SHIPPABLE CONDITION.  THE ID #'S ON THE CONTAINERS WERE G0586-004, G0281-325, G0281-318, G0586-054 AND G0586-55 AND WERE ASSOCIATED WITH LINE 3 OF MANIFEST 013080212FLE BASED ON THE LABEL INFORMATION. ALL OF THESE CONTAINERS WERE REMOVED FROM THE TRAILER. THE MATERIAL THAT HAD LEAKED ONTO THE VAN TRAILER FLOOR AND THE ASPHALT BELOW WERE BOTH CLEANED USING ABSORBENT MATERIALS AND WIPED WITH ABSORBENT PADS. TWO OF THE CONTAINER COMPLIANT FOR SHIPMENT PER DOT REGULATIONS. THE OTHER THREE CONTAINERS WERE FOUND TO HAVE MORE THAN 10 GALLONS OF FREE LIQUID IN THE BOTTOM OF EACH BOX. THEY ALSO HAD SEVERAL CONTAINERS IN THE GAYLORDS THAT WERE BROKEN OPEN. THESE THREE CONTAINERS WERE REPACKED INTO NEW GAYLORDS EXCEPT FOR THE FREE LIQUID OR OPEN CONTAINERS. THE LIQUID AND OPEN CONTAINERS WERE PLACED INTO TWO 55-GALLON STEEL DRUMS. THESE GAYLORDS WERE CONTAMINATED ON THE EXTERIOR FROM THE LEAKS AND THEY WERE FOLDED INTO A SUPER SACK WHICH REQUIRED THE CREATION OF A THIRD CONTAINER. ALL OF THE ORIGINAL GAYLORDS AND THE TWO OVERPACKED GAYLORDS WERE LOADED BACK INTO THE VAN. THE THREE CONTAINERS THAT WERE CREATED DURING THE EMERGENCY RESPONSE COULD NOT FIT ON THE ORIGINAL TRAILER, SO ARRANGEMENTS WERE MADE TO PICK THESE UP WITH ANOTHER TRAILER. THESE CONTAINERS WERE ADDED TO THE ORIGINAL MANIFEST PER THE DIRECTION OF THE GENERATOR. SPECIAL NOTE: WHILE REPACKING MATERIAL IN CONTAINER #G0281-318, NON-CONSUMER TYPE PAINT MATERIAL WAS FOUND. THIS PAINT HAD A METALLIC SHINE, WHICH INDICATES THE POSSIBILITY OF ALUMINUM PAINT. ALUMINUM PAINT IS NOT PROFILED UNDER WPS 53566 AND ALUMINUM PAINT REQUIRES SPECIAL HANDLING.
column169: WE WILL COMMUNICATE TO THE CUSTOMER THROUGH THE ROSS SALES TEAM TO ENSURE THAT PRIOR TO DEBRIS BEING LOADED INTO GAYLORDS, THAT LINERS ARE IN PLACE. INNER CONTAINERS MUST BE LOADED IN A MANNER THAT WILL PREVENT ANY OVER THE ROAD LEAKAGE.

column168: AT 0700 LOCAL TIME, A WAREHOUSE WORKER WAS UNLOADING WASTE DRUMS FROM A TRAILER AT THE FIRST DOCK AT BUILDING TWO. DURING OFF-LOADING THE TRAILER THE WORKER HAD TWO DRUMS ON THE PICKERS. AS THE EMPLOYEE WAS BACKING OFF THE TRAILER WITH THE TWO DRUMS THE BOLT OF ONE DRUM CAUGHT ON THE DRUM THAT WAS SPILLED AND TIPPED OVER THE DRUM. MATERIAL WENT DOWN THE DOCK INTO THE PARKING LOT AND TOWARD THE STORM DRAIN. THE EMPLOYEE RAN TO THE EMERGENCY SHUT OFF AND CLOSED THE DRAIN. SPEEDY DRY AND SPILL PADS WERE PUT DOWN TO CONTAIN THE SPILL. THE FACILITY MANAGER (FM) WAS CALLED AND THEN SHE CALLED AND REPORTED THE SPILL TO 1-855-NEXEO4U AND REPORTED THE SPILL TO A CORPORATE ENVIRONMENTAL RESPONDER (ER) AT 0710. THE ER THEN NOTIFIED THE NRC (INCIDENT NO. 1252240) AND THE NYDEC SPILL NO. (1903910).  AFTER ARRIVING AT THE PLANT THE FM CONTACTED ENVIRONMENTAL RESTORATION TO CLEAN UP THE SPILL. ER ARRIVED AT APPROXIMATELY 0900 ET AND HAD A VACUUM TRUCK ON THE WAY APPROXIMATELY AN HOUR AND A HALF OUT. EVALUATED THE SITUATION THERE WAS A MATERIAL IN ALL 3 STORM DRAINS ON SITE AND IN ONE STORM DRAIN ON THE SIDE OF THE ROAD OUTSIDE THE FENCED IN PROPERTY. SPILL PADS AND BOOMS WERE PUT INTO ALL THE STORM DRAINS. NYSDEC EMERGENCY RESPONSE COORDINATOR (JOHN KANE) ARRIVED ON SITE AT 0930 AND LOOKED OVER THE SITUATION. HE WAS PLEASED WITH THE PLANS THAT WERE IN PLACE AND INSTRUCTED ER TO CHECK THE MANHOLE COVER IN THE MIDDLE OF THE ROAD. THIS WAS CHECKED AND MATERIAL WAS OBSERVED IN THE PIPE LEADING TO THE DRAIN. CLEAN UP WAS DONE TO FOUR STORM DRAINS AND EACH DRAIN WAS FLUSHED WITH WATER ONCE THE VACUUM TRUCK ARRIVED AT APPROX 1230. MANHOLE COVER WAS REMOVED AND MATERIAL WAS REMOVED VIA VACUUM TANK. BACK DOCK WAS PRESSURE WASHED AND WATER WAS CONTAINED AND DRUMMED. ONE SAMPLE WAS TAKEN FROM THE SOLID MATERIAL THAT WAS REMOVED FROM THE STORM DRAINS AND COMPOSITE LIQUID SAMPLE WAS TAKEN FOR THE LIQUID MATERIAL. VACUUM TANK WAS EMPTIED INTO FOUR TOTES AND FOUR DRUMS. SOLID MATERIAL WAS PUT INTO 7 DRUMS. NOTE: THERE IS A FORMATTING ISSUE ON LINE 20 OF THIS DOCUMENT, THE MANIFEST NO. IS 02276677 FLE.
column169: RETRAIN FORKLIFT OPERATORS TO MAINTAIN SPACE THROUGH ALL MANEUVERS.  FLAMMABLE WASTE LIQUIDS WERE RECEIVED IN POLY DRUMS INSTEAD OF STEEL DRUMS.  STORM DRAIN COVERS WERE NOT ON THE STORM DRAINS WHILE UNLOADING THE DRUMS.

column168: US Ecology driver Victor Ferrufino was traveling westbound on Sam Houston Tollway on the downhill side of an overpass. A vehicle pulled out in front of him causing hard braking on the part of our driver. Victor pulled over to the construction are of the Sam Houston Tollway to check his load. Upon walking to the rear of the trailer, he noticed liquid coming out. He promptly called his supervisor Matt Boyette. Matt Boyette notified our internal US Ecology Response Team.  A Harris County Constable stopped and notified Houston Fire Department. Houston Fire Department contacted Masters ARS for cleanup. The leaking trailer was diked with a boom and oil dry. Houston Fire Department made entry into the trailer and found one 55 gallon poly closed top drum had been punctured and was leaking. The split was was in the middle of the drum side and had lost approximately 35 gallons. The damaged drum was over packed, the spill in the trailer was neutralized with Stardust. Spill on the roadway was neutralized and washed off by the fire department.
column169: Our investigation concluded that the force of the braking event caused the drum to slide slightly forward and the metal tensioner on a load-lock punctured the drum. We have suspended the use of load-locks and will be using nylon straps to secure loads.

column169: THE COMPANY HAS A ROLLOVER PREVENTION POLICY TITLED, "SLIP OFF STAY OFF" WITH CAB POSTERS AND TRAINING REMINDERS. THE IDEA IS TO BRING THE VEHICLE UNDER CONTROL WITHOUT ATTEMPTING TO RADICALLY CHANGE THE PATH WHICH CAN CAUSE LIQUID LOAD SHIFTING AND ADD TO THE POTENTIAL FOR OVERTURN. column168: DRIVER TOOK HIS EYES OFF THE ROADWAY TO LOOK AT HIS PHONE THAT HAD FALLIN ON THE FLOOR BOARD OF TRUCK. WHILE TRYING TO RETRIEVE HIS PHONE THE TRUCK DRIVER DROVE OFF THE ROADWAY WHICH RESULTED IN HIM OVERTURNING HIS TRUCK AND TRAILER. THE CRASH DENTED IN THE FRONT OF THE TRAILER CAUSING A WELD ON THE FIRST RIB TO CRACK OPEN APPROXIMATELY 2FT IN LENGTH AND START SPILLING CRUDE OIL OUT. DRIVER CALLED DISPATCH WHO CALLED THE NEW MEXICO STATE POLICE. A SECOND TRUCK ARRIVED MINUTES LATER AND BOTH DRIVERS TRIED TO DAM OFF THE SPILL AND SUCK CONTENTS FOR THE WRECKED TRAILER ONTO THE SECOND TRAILER. BECAUSE OF THE SIZE OF THE HOLE, OIL WAS COMING OUT FASTER THEN THEY COULD SUCK IT OFF SO UNTIL THE FLUID WAS BELOW THE CRACK OIL CONTINUED TO SPILL OUT. I ESTIMATE THIS LASTED ABOUT AN HOUR. EXCAVATION, RECLAMATION AND SOIL SAMPLE HAVE BEEN COMPLETED.
column169: WE HAVE SPECIAL TRAINING SET UP SEPTEMBER 10TH AND 11TH AT OUR LOCATIONS IN TEXAS IN WHICH EACH DRIVER WILL GO THROUGH DRIVER TRAINING AND BE TESTED IN A DRIVER SIMULATOR. WE HAVE INSTALLED A DEVICE IN ALL OUR TRUCKS THAT WILL PREVENT DRIVERS FROM TEXTING AND USING THERE APPS. WHILE THE TRUCK IS IN MOTION. WE HAVE FORWARD FACING CAMERA NOW BUT ARE IN THE PROCESS OF HAVING DUAL FACING CAMERAS INSTALLED SO WE CAN MONITOR HARSH EVENTS AND DISTRACTED DRIVERS. HOPEFULLY THIS WILL ALLOW US TO FIX THE PROBLEMS BEFORE AN ACCIDENT HAPPENS.

During routine facility operations, a containers closure was identified as seated improperly, resulting in small release of its contents. An internal emergency response team was immediately dispatched. In appropriate personal protective equipment, verified through the health and safety department, the response team safely overpacked the compromised container into an approved container for transportation. The release impact was contained to the warehouse floor, with no threat to water ways, storm drains, soil or environment. The container was sent to its final destination without further incident.
column169: An internal investigation was conducted and the drivers who accepted the containers were retrained on thorough container inspections with an emphasis on container closure. The generator was notified and are pursuing alternative means of approved containers.

Employees reported a strong odor of propane near GBRX 704013.  Upon inspection the Sample Line Valve was found in the open position with the plug less than tool tight.  The valve was closed and the release continued.  The plug was secured stopping the release.

Univar was making a multiple stop bleach delivery to our customer's Water Treatment plant.  The delivery was into a customer owned storage tank that failed.  The tank was a cone shaped bottom outlet 3500 gallon tank that leaked at the bottom.  As the tank was approaching maximum fill level, Univar's driver looked over the containment wall and noticed the tank was leaking. Univar's driver immediately shut down the product transfer and notified customer's personnel.   As plant personnel arrived, Univar's driver moved out of the way and was directed to complete delivery at their cooling tower, another delivery location on-site.

column168: A mini bulk driver was making a delivery of sodium hypochlorite to Trumbull Park in Chicago, IL. While unloading, he noticed product spraying from the 100 ft delivery hose near the trailer. He immediately shut down the delivery. He started placing pink pads on the spill area and blew down the line to eliminate pressure and product. He noticed some product creeping near a sewer drain and focused his clean-up efforts there first. He was able to soak product up using pink pads and absorbent. Another nearby driver was dispatched to assist the clean-up efforts. All solid waste was collected and properly disposed of at the warehouse. The estimated total loss is @ 10 gallons. The BOS immediately notified DOM and Regulatory.
column169: Hoses are being tested to determine failure point. Based on the identified issues from the test, hoses will be replaced as necessary.

column168: A Trimac tanker hauling residual UN1963 refrigerated liquid helium was involved in a single vehicle accident. The vent for the tankers onboard UN1977 liquid nitrogen cooling system was damaged which resulted in the release of liquid nitrogen. The tanker was secured and monitored while it vented approximately 100 pounds of liquid nitrogen. Once the tank pressure reached 2 PSI, the tanker was transported to a wrecker yard for further observation.

column168: A Clean Harbors semi-truck was transporting mixed load hazardous material from Wilmington to Utah.   During the course of the trip, the driver was pulled into the Cajon scale house for a routine  inspection.  A thorough inspection inside the trailer was conducted by CHP. It was determined that a leak was coming from a 55 gallon drum labeled as UN1791 with a hazardous waste label as  sodium hypochlorite.  Clean Harbors response team arrived on site, overpacked the leaking drum and cleaned up the spill material.  Local fire department assisted in providing technical reference  along with overseeing the cleanup.  No further spills were discovered inside the trailer.   It was determined that once the spill was cleaned up, the driver may continue the load to the  intended destination. Additional report made to Office of Emergency Services with report number 19-4543.
column169: After careful inspection of the drum prior to overpacking, a small rust area was noted and is believed to be the area from which the release occurred.   At the time the container was accepted for  transportation, no evidence of damage or leaking was observed.  Our drivers will continue to inspect each container during loading operation if present.  Furthermore warehouse personnel will continue to diligently inspect containers as they come in for continued transportation. In addition, the shipper will be advised of the situation and instructed to inspect all containers used for  the transport of waste materials to insure they meet all required specifications prior to offering them for transportation.

column168: At approximately 1430 hours Central Standard Time, a Clean Harbors Environmental Services, Inc. dock employee working at a Clean Harbors Environmental Services, Inc. facility located at 500 Independence Parkway, La Porte, Texas, 77571, noticed a spill on the inside floor of the trailer during the unloading process. Absorbent material was immediately put down and the spent product was contained. An in-house response crew responded to the spill, donned the appropriated PPE, and cleaned up the spill. Spilled material and absorbent materials used to remediate the spill were properly packaged, marked, and labeled and sent for disposal.
column169: An investigation into the spill incident revealed that the spill was due to a failed outlet valve gasket. The generator was alerted to the incident. column168: At 1600 ET, ERTS was notified by Kyle Goodwin with Dupre Logistics regarding a 20 gallon costic soda release that occurred at a customer location. The driver was of loading product when release happened. The initial cause is due to mechanical failure with the hose. ERTS Contacted the driver and was informed that only 2 gallons of product was released onto soil and the truck itself. No drain or waterways are reported to have been impacted by the release.  At 1621 ET, ERTS contacted Lone Star Hazmat for response, estimated ETA of 1730 ET.

column198: EMERGENCY RESPONSE AND TRAINING SOLUTIONS, INCORPORATED

column168: THE TIDEWATER TRANSIT VEHICLE WAS TRAVELING EASTBOUND ON I-20. AS THE VEHICLE WAS PASSING EXIT 58, A PASSENGER VEHICLE CAME DOWN THE ON-RAMP AND MERGED INTO THE TIDEWATER TRANSIT VEHICLE CAUSING IT TO OVERTURN AND LEAVE THE ROADWAY. THE OVERTURN CAUSED THE FIBERGLASS TANK TRAILER TO RUPTURE, RESULTING THE TOTAL LOSS OF THE LIQUID CARGO. THE RELEASED LIQUID IMPACTED THE PAVED ROADWAY, AND ROADSIDE DITCH WHERE IT WAS CONTAINED. THE RELEASED LIQUID WAS RECOVERED USING A VACUUM TANKER, AND TRANSPORTED OFF-SITE FOR DISPOSAL. IMPACTED SOIL WAS EXCAVATED AND TRANSPORTED TO THE LANDFILL FOR DISPOSAL. THE AREA WAS RESTORED TO PRE-EXISTING CONDITIONS.  THE TIDEWATER TRANSIT DRIVER WAS NOT FOUND AT FAULT FOR THE INCIDENT.  THE RELEASE WAS REPORTED TO THE NATIONAL RESPONSE CENTER AT 1507 HOURS ON 7/13/19. THE RELEASE WAS ALSO REPORTED TO THE SOUTH CAROLINA DEPARTMENT O HEALTH AND ENVRIONMENTAL CONTROL.

column169: WHEN DRUMS ARE LOADED THEY MUST BE SECURED WITH STRAPS, LOAD BARS OR PALLETS TO SECURE THE DRUMS SO THEY DON'T SHIFT DURING TRANSIT WILL BE THE MESSAGE TO ALL FREIGHT LOADERS.

column42: SULFURIC ACID WITH MORE THAN 51 PERCENT ACID
column168: THE DRIVER CAME TO AN ABRUPT STOP DURING A TRAFFIC LIGHT CHANGE. DURING THE STOP ONE IBC TOTE OUT OF A TOTAL OF TEN SLIPPED OUT OF THE STRAPS AND FELL FORWARD AND SIDEWAYS OFF THE FLATBED TRAILER ONTO THE GROUND. THE IBC TOTE CAP HAD ABOUT A HALF INCH CRACK DUE TO IMPACT, WHICH CAUSED 75 GALLONS OF SULFURIC ACID TO LEAK OUT. AT THIS TIME THE PROPER PERSONAL WAS CALLED TO THE SCENE TO SAFETY REMEDY THE SITUATION. MASTER ARE CLEAN UP SERVICES USED AN EPOXY TO STOP THE LEAK AT THE CAP. AFTER CONTAINMENT THE CLEANUP DURATION WAS BETWEEN 4 TO 5 HOURS.
column169: SINCE THE ACCIDENT, WE WERE ABLE TO IMPLEMENT ADDITIONAL TRAINING AND A REFRESHER TO OUR PERSONNEL ON HOW TO SAFELY SECURE AND TRANSPORT SHIPMENTS. STRAPPING, LOAD POSITIONING, AND DRIVING CONDITIONS WERE ALL REVAMPED AND RETRAINED TO ENSURE REOCCURRENCE WILL NOT HAPPEN AGAIN. ALSO, DUE TO THE STRAPS LOOSENING IN TRANSIT, FROM NOW ON THE DRIVER WILL HAVE TO STOP AND  CHECK TIGHTNESS OF STRAPS THROUGHOUT TRANSIT UNTIL THEY REACH THEIR DESTINATION. WE BELIEVE THE IBC TOTES USED IN THIS SHIPMENT WERE WEAKENED DUE TO PREVIOUS USE IN OTHER SHIPMENTS. THE PLASTIC MATERIAL ON THE TOP OF THE IBC TOTE NEEDS TO BE OF HEAVIER GRADE PLASTIC OR METAL. STRAPS TEND TO LOOSEN WHILE IN TRANSIT ON CURRENT TOTES, SO FOR EXAMPLE, AFTER THE DRIVER LEAVES PICK UP THEY WILL HAVE TO CHECK STRAPS AT THE 10 MILE, 30 MILE, 60 MILE AND SO ON UNTIL THEY REACH THE DELIVERY DESTINATION TO ENSURE SAFE TRANSPORT.

column42: GASOLINE INCLUDES GASOLINE MIXED WITH ETHYL ALCOHOL, WITH NOT MORE THAN 10% ALCOHOL
column168: In the early morning of July 18, 2019, a tanker truck owned by Delaney Fuel Transport LLC hit an island in the middle of Sisson Road in Harwich Port and flipped onto its side.  When the truck flipped onto its side, gasoline leaked from the tanker and ran down both sides of Sisson Road.  The Harwich Fire and Police Departments responded swiftly and, working with the Harwich DPW, secured/evacuated the area and worked to contain the spilled gasoline.  Prior to their arrival, gasoline flowed into and through the storm drain system, located under Sisson Road, in a southerly direction, past Route 28, and into a drainage swale south of Route 28.  Gasoline pooled in the drainage swale.  Approximately 8,500 gallons of gasoline was recovered from the overturned tanker.  The volume of gasoline released to the environment is estimated at 3,825 gallons. Edge worked to recover spilled gasoline by pumping out storm drains, catch basins and a drainage swale, and by deploying sorbents to the storm drain system and swale. Truck
column172: Tank truck, tank mounted on truck chassis

column168: The product that was damaged was packaged in a corrugated box with a plastic liner containing the hydrochloric acid.  A dock worker was repositioning the skid inside the trailer when he had the forks on the forklift angled upwards and stabbed the box and bag of hydrochloric acid.  The dock worker could smell the acid and exited the trailer and alerted the Supervisor on duty of the spill.  As the Supervisor approached the trailer and could smell the odor, he instructed the yard jockey to pull the trailer away from the dock and placed it away from the dock, drains, and employee access.  Within minutes of the initial spill, the trailer was removed from the dock and placed in the western drop areas of the yard away from people, building, drains, and other freight.  The fire department was called and arrived at the scene, were escorted to the trailer, given the bills of lading to identify the freight that was damaged, and immediately secured the scene. The fire department Hazardous Material response team isolated the damaged freight, placed the remaining liquid into an over-pack drum, placed the packaging and clean up materials into Haz-Mat bags, secured the bags, and left the scene.  Veolia was contacted the next day to arrange for proper disposal of the over-pack drum and Haz-Mat bags which was completed 8/6/19.   The release was contained within the confines of the trailer and never made contact with the ground.  The fire department utilized clay absorbent materials to contain and recover the leaking fluid within the trailer and that product was also contained within the Haz-Mat bags.   The trailer was neutralized with a acid neutralizer and water and pressure washed to ensure no further exposure to the leaking product.
column169: The root cause was driver error.  The forklift operator had his forks angled upwards versus level or slightly downward when he attempted to move the skid within the trailer.  His forks made contact with the pallet runners and due to the upward angle stabbed the box and subsequent inner bag containing the Hydrochloric Acid causing a release. The operator has been retrained and a new procedures has been developed and implemented regarding the handing of hazardous materials within the trailers.   Hazardous materials will only be handled by high level trained forklift operators certified not only in the safe handling, but identification of hazardous materials.  In addition, the shipper will be placing the hazardous materials on the tail of the trailer to minimize exposure to material handling and freight damage caused by material handling and cargo securement.

column42: SULFURIC ACID WITH MORE THAN 51 PERCENT ACID
column168: Driver was delivering three loads the day before. After he was completed he ended up scaling out and had approximately a 836 gallon heel of Sulfuric Acid that was on his trailer. He then proceeded back to the plant to drop off his tractor/trailer. The next day the same driver was loading on top of the heel and forgot he had a heel on his trailer. When he was loading the emergency shut off floaty was not inserted into the trailer. The emergency shut off floaty would have shut off the pump when the product reaches a certain capacity in the trailer. He end up loading 3,870 gallons of Sulfuric Acid in a 4,000 gallon trailer with approximately a 836 gallon heel. Approximately 630 gallons of Sulfuric Acid was released into containment and contained inside PVS Transportation property. The approximate duration of the release was 2 minutes. The driver was notified by maintenance he was leaking product onto the ground and shut off the loading operations. The team ended up neutralizing the Sulfuric Acid with Soda Ash and was cleaned up.
column169: One of the corrective actions was the employee is no longer with the company. Also, PVS Transportation tank truck loading form will be updated to include verification the emergency floaty is inserted into the trailer. We will also, be auditing these forms on a frequent basis to verify completeness and compliance.

column168: ON 7-25-19 A PACKAGE WAS DISCOVERED IN THE SORT AISLE WITH A SMALL AMOUNT OF LIQUID COMING FROM THE CORNER. THE FIRST RESPONDER WAS CALLED AND UPON FURTHER INSPECTION REALIZED THAT THE PACKAGE WAS A HAZMAT. THE PACKAGE WAS OVER BOXED AND HAD NO EXTERNAL MARKINGS OTHER THAN THE ADDRESS LABEL. THE INNER BOX WAS LABELED WITH A FLAMMABLE 3 DIAMOND AND CLASS 3, P.G.II UN1197.

column168: ON JULY 3RD 2019 AT APPROXIMATELY 11:55 AM MY DRIVER DISCOVERED THAT HE WAS LEAKING AMMONIUM NITRATE FROM HIS TANKER. HE IMMEDIATELY PULLED OVER AND CALLED OUR OPERATIONS DEPARTMENT AND ADVISED THEM HE HAD A VERY SMALL LEAK COMING FROM THE REAR OF HIS TRAILER. OUR OPERATIONS DEPARTMENT THEN NOTIFIED OUR SHOP WHO WENT TO THE SCENE TO REPAIR THE TRAILER. AT APPROXIMATELY 2:00 PM THE SAFETY DEPARTMENT WAS NOTIFIED OF THE SITUATION. THE SAFETY DEPARTMENT CALLED THE FIELD MANAGER ON THE GROUND TO ACCESS THE SITUATION. AS THE SAFETY MANAGER WAS PREPARING TO NOTIFY THE AUTHORITIES THE FIRE DEPARTMENT HAD ALREADY ARRIVED ON SCENE. THE FIRE DEPARTMENT AND THE COLORADO STATE PATROL SHUT DOWN THE HIGHWAY. WE WORKED CLOSELY WITH THE AUTHORITIES AND SENT ANOTHER DRIVER TO TRANSLOAD THE PRODUCT ONTO ANOTHER TRAILER. WE ALSO HAD SPILL CONTAINMENT ON SCENE TO PREVENT THE PRODUCT FROM RELEASING INTO THE ENVIRONMENT. WE ESTIMATE 20-30 GALLONS OF PRODUCT WAS RELEASED. THIS PRODUCT IS UNIQUE  AS IT IS KEPT HEATED TO KEEP IT AT A LIQUID STATE. ONCE THE PRODUCT DROPS BELOW 167 DEGREES FAHRENHEIT IT STARTS TURNING INTO A SOLID CRYSTALLINE SALT LIKE MATERIAL. THE MAJORITY OF THE MATERIAL THAT HIT THE GROUND WAS IN A SOLID FORM.  ONCE THE TRANSLOAD WAS COMPLETED, THE CLEANING GUYS ENVIRONMENT CLEAN UP COMPLETED THE CLEANUP OF ALL PRODUCT THAT WAS ON THE ROAD.  ONCE THE STATE PATROL RELEASED OUR EQUIPMENT, WE TOOK IT TO OUR YARD IN COLORADO SPRINGS. A COUPLE OF DAYS LATER THE TRAILER WAS TRANSPORTED TO POLAR SERVICE CENTERS FOR REPAIR AND RETESTING. POLAR DISCOVERED ABOUT A DIME SIZED HOLE ON THE BACK OF THE TANKER NEAR THE LADDER. THE TRAILER WAS REPAIRED AND PASSED THE RETEST. THE FIRST VIK INSPECTION AND THE REPAIR ORDER ARE INCLUDED WITH THIS REPORT.  WE DO NOT THINK OUR DRIVER WAS AT FAULT. HE THOROUGHLY INSPECTED HIS TRAILER BEFORE HE LEFT THIS DAY AS WELL AS AFTER HE GOT LOADED. THE TRAILER DEVELOPED A CRACK WHILE IN TRANSIT. THE TRAILER HAD JUST GONE THROUGH ITS VIK/CARGO TANK INSPECTION AND CERTIFICATION BY AN R STAMP CERTIFIED SHOP ON MAY 2, 2019 AND PASSED. US TRANSPORT PRIDES ITSELF ON SAFETY AND SAFE OPERATING PROCEDURES AND WILL CONTINUE TO OPERATE AT THE HIGHEST LEVEL OF SAFETY AND COMPLIANCE.
column169: CORRECTIVE ACTIONS - RETRAINING WITH ALL OPERATIONS STAFF, DRIVERS AND MAINTENANCE STAFF  ON EMERGENCY PROCEDURES FOLLOWING A HAZARDOUS MATERIAL RELEASE. WE HAVE ALSO HAD ONE ON ONE MEETINGS WITH ALL HAZMAT DRIVERS REGARDING EQUIPMENT INSPECTIONS AND INCIDENT REPORTING PROTOCOL. COMPLETE HAZMAT RE-TRAINING ON ALL HAZMAT DRIVERS WILL BE COMPLETED BEFORE THE END OF THE YEAR, EVEN THOUGH THEIR TRAINING IS CURRENTLY UP TO DATE.

column168: THE PETRO CHEMICAL TRANSPORT, LLC DRIVER WAS ATTEMPTING TO DELIVER DIESEL FUEL INTO THE CUSTOMER'S STORAGE TANK. IN THE COURSE OF DOING SO, HE OVERFILLED THE STORAGE TANK AND APPROXIMATELY 10 GALLONS OF DIESEL FUEL WAS RELEASED. A LOCAL ENVIRONMENTAL CONTRACTOR RESPONDED TO THE SCENE AND HANDLED THE REMEDIATION. NO FURTHER ENVIRONMENTAL IMPACT IS ANTICIPATED.
column169: PETRO CHEMICAL TRANSPORT, LLC WILL CONTINUE TO TRAIN AND ENFORCE SAFE LOADING/UNLOADING POLICIES AND PROCEDURES.

column168: PASSENGER VEHICLE WAS ONCOMING AND DRIFTING OVER CENTER LINE, DID NOT RESPOND TO AIR HORN WARNING. THE CARGO DID NOT LEAK AND THERE WAS NO FAILURE OF ANY COMPONENT ON TRAILER CONTAINING CARGO, ALTHOUGH THE TRAILER DID SUFFER SERIOUS DAMAGE RESULTING IN INOPERABILITY. THE SPILL WAS REPORTED TO THE NEW YORK DEPARTMENT OF ENVIRONMENT CONSERVATION, SPILL NUMBER NYDEC # 1903726. column168: OUR TRANSPORT TANKER HAD JUST COMPLETED LOADING A LOAD OF DIESEL FUEL AT THE NUSTAR TERMINAL IN NORFOLK, NE AND WAS EXITING LOCATION ONTO A FOUR LANE HIGHWAY OF WHICH TRUCK HAD TO CROSS TWO N BOUND LANES BEFORE ENTERING THE S BOUND LANES. BEFORE TRAILER CLEARED COMPLETELY OUT OF N BOUND LANES IT WAS STRUCK IN CENTER LANE BY N BOUND TRUCK (FACTOR WAS VISIBILITY-FOG). N BOUND TRUCK STRUCK TANK RIGHT IN FRONT OF TRAILER AXELS CAUSING A 4-6 INCH PUNCTURE HOLE 1/2 UP SIDE ON COMPARTMENT 4 IN RESULT OF 400 GALLON RELEASE OF DIESEL. ALSO IMPACT RESULTED IN COMPARTMENT 5 FIRE VALVE AND 4" PIPE TO BE SHEERED OFF ON UNDERSIDE OF TANK WITH A RESULT OF 2300 GALLON RELEASE OF DIESEL.   DIRT WAS HAULED IN TO CONTAIN THE SPILL AND HAZ-MAT  EMERGENCY RESPONSE TEAM WAS CALLED TO THE LOCATION FOR CLEANUP. MOST OF THE FUEL WAS CONTAINED IN THE MEDIAM AND MEDIUM WAS IN WEST DITCH.  THE RELEASE OUT OF HOLE ON SIDE OF TANK LEAKED FOR APPROX. 1 HOUR WHILE OTHER TRUCK WAS CALLED IN TO OFF LOAD THE TANKER. HOWEVER , THE 2300 GALLON RELEASE WAS INSTANTANEOUS SINCE IMPACT SHEERED OFF A 4" PIPE FROM BOTTOM SIDE OF TANKER.
column169: IN THIS PARTICULAR ACCIDENT I DO NOT SEE HOW ANY CHANGES COULD BE MADE TO AVOID THE RELEASE OF PRODUCT, IT WAS A VERY UNFORTUNATE ACCIDENT OF WHICH OUR EMPLOYEES AND THE CALLED IN HAZ-MAT CREW HANDLED VERY PROFESSIONALLY.

column168: THE TRUCK OPERATOR WAS PLANNING TO MANUALLY TOP LOAD THE CMTV. THE LOADING WAS IMMEDIATELY STOPPED BY THE TRUCK OPERATOR AND FACILITY PERSONNEL NOTIFIED. FACILITY PERSONNEL IMMEDIATELY PUT DOWN ABSORBENT TO CONTAIN THE RELEASE. THE MATERIAL WAS COLLECTED AND PLACED IN DRUMS THAT WERE SHIPPED OFF-SITE FOR PROPERTY TREATMENT/DISPOSAL.  NO IMPACT TO STORMWATER DRAINS OF THE SUBSURFACE OCCURRED (RELEASE TO CONCRETE/ASPHALT SURFACE ONLY).

column168: The truck operator was bottom loading his CMTV with a pre-set amount. The filling did not stop when the pre-set was reached or when the Scully on-board system high level was also reached. Shut down of the bay was required to stop flow. Subsequent investigation revealed a tear in a diaphragm inside a rack valve that is is involved in product flow to the filling trucks. No package failure occurred. Facility personnel immediately put down absorbent to contain the release. The material was collected and placed in drums that were shipped off-site for property treatment disposal. No impact to storm-water drains or the subsurface occurred (release to concrete/asphalt surface only).

column168: DRIVER WAS DELIVERING 1000 GALLONS CITRA GUARD XP FLORIDA FERTILIZER IN WACHULA FL. THIS PRODUCT A MICRO-NUTRIENT FERTILIZER BLEND IN AN HDPE PORTABLE TANK WE BELIEVE TO BE APPROPRIATE FOR THIS MATERIAL (CFR 172. 102 SPECIAL PROVISION 58 AND CFR 173.154 EXEMPTION). UPON ARRIVAL, CUSTOMER WANTED PRODUCT TRANSFERRED INTO THEIR 250 GAL IBC TANKS. DRIVER PUMPED PRODUCT TO FIRST IBC, WENT TO CLOSE VALVE TO GET READY TO TRANSFER TO NEXT IBC WHEN PVC PIPING BETWEEN VALVE AND TANK BROKE OFF ENTIRELY, RELEASING 750 GAL OF REMAINING PRODUCT IN APPROXIMATELY 10 MINUTES. TANK WAS UNDAMAGED.  NATIONAL RESPONSE CENTER WAS NOTIFIED BY FLORIDA FERTILIZER. RESPONSE EFFORTS WERE CO-ORDINATED BETWEEN FLORIDA DEP AND FLORIDA FERTILIZER. THEIR EMPLOYEES AND OUR DRIVER DIKED AREA WITH DIRT TO CONTAIN MATERIAL. MATERIAL WAS ABSORBED INTO DIRT, AND TRANSFERRED TO STORAGE FOR AGRONOMIC APPLICATION AS FERTILIZER ACCORDING TO PRODUCT LABELED APPLICATION RATES (6.25 LBS PER ACRE).

column168: THE MC 331 TANK CAME UNATTACHED FROM THE TRACTOR ON MCCORMICK ROAD AND LANDED ON THE ASPHALT ROADWAY ON THE TANK'S KINGPIN PLATE AND ROLLED-UP DOLLY LEGS. THE LEGS WERE BRACED TO THE PRODUCT PUMP AND UNDERCARRIAGE. THIS RESULTED IN THE PUMP SHEARING OFF THE ADJACENT INTERNAL VAPOR VALVE. THE VALVE WAS COCKED AT AN ANGLE. THIS ALLOWED VAPOR TO SPRAY INTO ATMOSPHERE. AFTER THE UNIT WAS BROUGHT BACK TO THE TRUCKING COMPANY TERMINAL (4.7 MILES AWAY) THE TANK OFF-LOADED ONTO ANOTHER EMPTY MC 331 TANKER. ONCE THE VAPOR PRESSURE IN THE DAMAGED TANK HAD BEEN REDUCED TO 20#, THE VAPOR INTERNAL WAS TAPPED WITH A HAMMER AND IT RE-SEALED ITSELF SHUT. THE ENTIRE PROCESS FROM ACCIDENT TO FINISH LASTED 5.5 HOURS. THE RANDALL COUNTY FIRE AND SHERIFF DEPARTMENT MONITORED THE ACCIDENT SCENE FOR APPROXIMATELY 4 HOURS BEFORE THE WRECKER WAS ALLOWED TO LIFT UP AND REMOVE THE TANKER TRAILER. OFFLOADING THE REMAINING PRODUCT TOOK ANOTHER 90 MINUTES.
column169: RE-TRAINED FLEET ON PROPER COUPLING AND UNCOUPLING PROCEDURES BY ASSIGNING ON-LINE INFINIT-I TRAINING TO ALL DRIVERS. THE TANKER HAD BEEN "HIGH-HOOKED" WITH THE BOTTOM SITTING ON TOP OF THE FIFTH WHEEL LOCKING JAWS. THE TOP OF THE JAWS WERE WIPED CLEAN OF GREASE FROM THE KINGPIN PRESSING IT OUT AS IT SLID OFF THE TRACTOR. THE DRIVER HAD JUST PICKED UP THE LOADED TRAILER ON THE YARD LESS THAN 5 MILES AWAY. THE DRIVER WAS TERMINATED.

column168: During unloading process, driver noticed a leak at the hose connection. Driver shut down offloading attempted to disconnect the hose to properly align and reconnect. Some pressure on the hose product sprayed product on drivers PPE. Fumes went into drivers face and eyes causing irritation. Driver washed face and eyes removing product residue. Driver completed unloading operations without further incident. Driver required no medical attention from incident.
column169: Reinforce driver training concerning loading and unloading operations specific to connection or disconnecting hoses under pressure.
column172: Tank truck, tank mounted on truck chassis

column168: UPT driver was dispatched to deliver fuel to OG&E in Muskogee, OK. OG&E requested too much fuel than their AST could fit. While offloading, OG&E's 90% and 95% overfill protection devices failed resulting in an estimated 50-gallon diesel spill as well as a violation of the Oklahoma Corporation Commission regulation 165:26-2-5.1. General spill and overfill prevention requirements (D). Upon release of product, driver shut off pump and called safety. Safety called US Ecology, who then notified Heritage Environmental whom rent to scene to begin remediation.
column169: It has been suggested that the owner of an AST follows the following regulations established by the OCC;  (d) For installations after October 13, 2018, a fill valve which automatically stops delivery of liquid when the tank reaches ninety-five percent (95%) capacity in addition to one of the following methods must be used to prevent overfilling. column168: As driver departed gate from shipper location, he noticed spillage in his mirror, returned to shipper's facility for inspection and corrective action. Inspections showed shipper personnel failed to properly secured dome lid causing product to release into dike area at top of tank. Dome properly secured, leak ended. Shipper personnel cleaned product from top of tank in containment area. Unit returned to full service, delivery made without further incident.
column169: Reinforce training for shipper loading personnel to ensure all valves and openings are closed upon completion of loading before releasing CTMV to driver.

column168: Upon completion of unloading process, driver disconnected unloading hose from CTMV causing an spill due to failure to close off consignee's storage tank's valve prior to disconnecting hose. Product flow back from storage tank through hose before driver could shut off valve at consignees receiving tank. Contractor performed cleaned-up as required and process properly.
column169: Retrain driver on proper unloading procedures concerning connection and disconnection of unloading hose line. Verification that all valves are closed prior to disconnecting hoses.

column168: During unloading process product leaked due to loose butterfly nut on external valve. Driver tightened the twist on the butterfly nut stopping the leak. Consignee's personnel cleaned-up and processed properly

column168: Driver hooked up the vapor hose and there was an extreme amount of pressure that was in the ground.  He then hooked up the drop hose and opened the external and the internal valve.  Once the Internal valve was opened, the drop hose shook rather hard and twisted, causing the dog ears to come loose and  the hose came off the drop gun.  This caused about 10 to 15 gallons to spill on the concrete.  Driver called 911 and the Fire Dept. came, using one 50 pound bag of floor dry to stop and dry up the fuel.  A couple of drops did make it to the drain, but the Fire Dept. used about 100 to 150 gallons of Spray water to flush the drain before leaving the scene.  Driver cleaned up the floor dry and took it back to the KSCY terminal.
column169: Drive was retrained on fueling procedures and counseled on the importance of following the appropriate steps in the order they are written.

column168: FORKLIFT DRIVER WAS MOVING A PALLET OF 4 HM DRUMS FROM THE DOCK TO THE TRAILER @ ROSS EXPRESS HERMON, ME TERMINAL LOADING DOCK. THE FORKLIFT OPERATOR MISJUDGED THE EDGE OF THE DOCK PLATE WITH THE FORKS UNDER DRUMS OF HM AND DAMAGED THE 2 DRUMS. THIS ACTION CAUSED THE EDGE OF DOCK PLATE TO PUNCTURE THE DRUMS CREATING A HOLE IN THE BOTTOM OF THE 2 DRUMS. TWO TO THREE GALLONS OF HM PRODUCT LEAKED ON THE DOCK. FORKLIFT OPERATOR ACTED QUICKLY AND NOTIFIED HIS IMMEDIATE SUPERVISOR WHO INSTRUCTED FORKLIFT OPERATOR TO USE PADS THAT WERE LAID DOWN ON THE DOCK AND DRUMS WERE UPRIGHTED TO STOP THE LEAK. THE SUPERVISOR CHECKED HIS SDS BOOK AND EMERGENCY RESPONSE GUIDBOOK FOR INSTRUCTIONS. THIS EVENT STARTED @ 6:30AM. THE COMPANY EMPLOYEES CLEANED UP THE HM PRODUCT AND WAS DISPOSING OF THE MATERIAL AND CLEANUP PADS TO A 2 CONTAINMENT DRUMS BEING SHIPPED TO BACK TO THE CUSTOMER TO SAVE THE REMAINING PRODUCT IN THE 2 DRUMS. THE PRODUCT THAT SPILLED WAS VERY THIN ALMOST LIKE ALCOHOL OR PAINT THINNER, IT SEEMED TO EVAPORATE QUICKLY AND DID NOT LEAVE A RESIDUE. THE DOCK FLOOR WAS CLEANED AND ALLOW TO VENT. ARRANGEMENTS WERE MADE WITH THE CONSIGNEE. THE 2 CONTAINMENT DRUMS WAS PLACED IN A SECURED AREA UNTIL THEY COULD SAFETY TRANSPORTED TO THE CONSIGNEE TO RETRIEVE THE REMAINING PRODUCT FOR REPACKAGE.
column169: FORKLIFT OPERATOR HAS BEEN COUNSELED ON THE PROPER USE OF FORKLIFT EQUIPMENT AT OUR COMPANY BY HIS SUPERVISOR.

column168: Driver stated that during loading the hose burst and about 30 gallons of Crude Oil/condensate spilled onto the gravel.  The loading facility does a check for gases in the air while they are loading, and it appeared on camera that the hose moved before it burst which showed that it was under pressure.  There is condensate in the hoses from the heat, and the gases build pressure inside the hose causing it to burst.  The Driver uses the facility's vapor and loading hoses.  Their Safety Dept. came out and looked at the camera footage and determined that their hose was weak and burst. There are no drains nearby.  The facility cleaned up the spill and placed rocks on top.  Driver is on standby as gases are still coming up out of the ground.
column169: No retraining necessary, this was equipment failure.

column168: Upon arrival, the driver connected Comp. 1 to the E. tank, opened the internal/external valves and about 1 minute later ULSD began spilling out of the vapor line and the vapor line relief valve. The driver immediately closed the internal/external valves, placed his bucket under the relief valve (which was being utilized) and notified the store, Planning Center and Safety. Loves provided boom socks for containment and the Planning Center instructed the driver to contact his TM & Safety. Field Safety Coordinator confirmed the spill was contained and there was no product flowing to any Storm Water Drainage (the spill was contained underneath the GTI trailer) in an area approx. 20' X 10'.  Loves Travel Center notified their response team who responded and provided cleanup. While FSC was talking to the driver, the Loves Mechanic came over and said that the same thing happened to one of the Loves Refine trucks the week before (except the spill was bigger). FSC instructed the driver to not attempt any further unloading and to not leave until the vapor line pressure is reduced and the vapor line is emptied. FSC contacted the KSCY SM who provided assistance to the driver, via phone, on how to relieve the pressure and empty the vapor line. The Loves Response Team assisted with emptying the vapor line into the E. tank. The driver stated that he got a veeder reading prior to unloading, but did not stick the tanks because the sticks will not reach the bottom. Due to Loves having this same problem the week before, FSC felt this spill may be due to an issue with the Loves tanks, and instructed the driver to take the loaded truck back to the KSCY Term, leave the Tractor under the Trailer and lock both units OOS.
column169: This was caused by a defective tank at the store.
